The problem with using `Collections.unmodifiableList` is that you&#39;re not really creating a read-only view on mutable collection, not real immutable collection. It might seem like it&#39;s not a big deal, but in reality, the mutable collection acting as immutable won&#39;t be very efficient and performant. For example, appending the new element to the list would require copying the whole list.

I would suggest you check out [Vavr](https://www.vavr.io/vavr-docs/). It has its own implementation of functional, immutable [linked list](https://www.vavr.io/vavr-docs/#_linked_list), which allows you to do appends on constant time (which doesn&#39;t require copying whole list, because common elements are shared). For example:

    var l1 = List.of(1, 2, 3); //List(1, 2, 3)
    var l2 = l1.append(4);     //List(1, 2, 3, 4)

In this example both list would share 1,2,3.

You can also convert from and to Java List easily:

    java.util.List&lt;String&gt; javaList = Arrays.asList(&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Haskell&quot;, &quot;Scala&quot;);
    List&lt;String&gt; vavrList = List.ofAll(javaList);

    List&lt;String&gt; vavrStringList = List.of(&quot;JAVA&quot;, &quot;Javascript&quot;, &quot;Scala&quot;);
    java.util.List&lt;String&gt; javaStringList = vavrStringList.toJavaList();

You could use [collectingAndThen](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#collectingAndThen-java.util.stream.Collector-java.util.function.Function-):

        myList.stream()
                .filter(item -&gt; someMethod(item))
                .map(item -&gt; doSomething(item))
                .collect(Collectors.collectingAndThen(Collectors.toList(), result -&gt; {
                    if (result.isEmpty()) throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Empty!!&quot;);
                    return result;
                }));

Since there is no straight forward way of https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26649062/how-to-check-if-a-java-8-stream-is-empty, a much preferrable code would be :

    List&lt;SomeObject&gt; output = myList.stream()
            .filter(item -&gt; someMethod(item))
            .map(item -&gt; doSomething(item))
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
    if (!myList.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; output.isEmpty()) {
        throw new RuntimeException(&quot;your message&quot;);
    } 


----------


Another alternative to this could be using `noneMatch`, to validate before the execution such as:

    if (myList.stream().noneMatch(item -&gt; someMethod(item))) {
        throw new RuntimeException(&quot;your message&quot;);
    }

